{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496979"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:01:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:01:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1450"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1450"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.02,0.1,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29125"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1450"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15284"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"8814"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43981"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/29125"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents with a two-day history of blurred vision, increased sensitivity to light and a gritty sensation in her right eye. She does not wear contact lenses and has no relevant medical history. She has never experienced anything like this before.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA slit lamp examination with fluorescein staining is performed (Image).\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aciclovir\u00a03% eye ointment","Azithromycin\u00a01g","Chloramphenicol\u00a00.5% eye drops","Ciprofloxacin\u00a00.3% eye drops","Dexamethasone 0.1% eye drops"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eherpes simplex keratitis. \u003C/strong\u003EThe blurry vision, photophobia and foreign-body sensation suggest keratitis, and the branching (dendritic) ulcer seen on fluorescein staining of the corneal surface is highly suggestive of herpes simplex keratitis. The treatment of dendritic ulcers in adults is \u003Cstrong\u003Eaciclovir\u0026nbsp;3% eye ointment topically\u003C/strong\u003E into the affected eye, 5 times daily for 10 to 14 days, or for at least 3 days after healing (whichever is shorter).\u0026nbsp;Infective keratitis is a sight-threatening emergency, so an urgent referral to an ophthalmologist is warranted. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf topical eye ointment is not available, then it is acceptable to use oral antiviral therapy for herpes simplex keratitis, \u003Cstrong\u003Evalaciclovir\u0026nbsp;or aciclovir\u0026nbsp;orally \u003C/strong\u003Efor 7-10 days. Patients must also be educated about the probability of future recurrences, for recurrent herpes simplex keratitis consider long-term suppressive oral antiviral therapy in consultation with an ophthalmologist. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAzithromycin\u0026nbsp;1 g\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in the management of herpes simplex keratitis. It is the first-line management of chlamydial conjunctivitis which usually presents as acute\u0026nbsp;unilateral conjunctivitis with mucopurulent discharge. A dendritic ulcer would not be present in chlamydial conjunctivitis.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiprofloxacin 0.3% eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E have no role in herpes simplex keratitis. They are indicated as the first-line therapy in bacterial keratitis, in conjunction with an urgent referral to an ophthalmologist. Bacterial keratitis usually occurs in contact lens wearers and patients with a compromised ocular surface. In bacterial keratitis, the patient\u0027s symptoms would include pain, photophobia and reduced vision, and a white spot is often seen on the cornea.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChloramphenicol\u0026nbsp;0.5% eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E are not used in the management of herpes simplex dendritic ulcers. Chloramphenicol eye drops or ointment are used as prophylaxis in corneal abrasions, and following the removal of corneal foreign bodies. A foreign body would present with a similar history to this case, however, a foreign would usually be visualised on the slit-lamp examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETopical steroids such as \u003Cstrong\u003Edexamethasone 0.1%\u003C/strong\u003E are contraindicated in the presence of herpes simplex epithelial keratitis. Their use may result in stromal necrosis, corneal perforation, secondary microbial infections, visual loss and they have been implicated in prolonging the course of herpetic eye disease. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A dendritiform ulcer seen on fluorescein staining of the cornea is highly suggestive of herpes simplex keratitis"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Keratitis. Therapeutic guidelines. Updated April, 2019. Accessed October 11, 2022. https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.eu1.proxy.openathens.net/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Antibiotic\u0026topicfile=keratitis","Sugar A. Herpes simplex keratitis. UpToDate. Updated June 21, 2021. Accessed October 11, 2022. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/herpes-simplex-keratitis?search=dendritic%20ulcer%20\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15284"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1450"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17750"},{"type":"media","id":"17751"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17750"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5402dd10-899a-433d-912d-7e3930be4d0f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5402dd10-899a-433d-912d-7e3930be4d0f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":391}},{"type":"media","id":"17751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17751"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9a28a626-152f-4300-9157-39c12cd1313e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9a28a626-152f-4300-9157-39c12cd1313e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":408}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/15284"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-10-13T12:51:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-10-13T12:51:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1450"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29125"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount